            <fr:anchor>10390</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KK</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00KK.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Inductive definitions">Inductive definitions</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>We have already seen some inductive definitions:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:link href="jms-00JE.xml" title="Iteration of endo-relations" addr="jms-00JE" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00JE" /></fr:link> defines <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-fold iterations</html:span> of <fr:link href="jms-00JC.xml" title="Directed graph" addr="jms-00JC" type="local">endo-relations</fr:link> by induction on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:link href="jms-00JV.xml" title="The adjacency matrix of the reflexive-transitive closure" addr="jms-00JV" type="local">Algorithm <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00JV" /></fr:link> computes the <fr:link href="jms-00JN.xml" title="Adjacency matrix of a finite directed graph" addr="jms-00JN" type="local">adjacency matrix</fr:link> of the <fr:link href="jms-00JH.xml" title="The reflexive-transitive closure of an endo-relation" addr="jms-00JH" type="local">reflexive-transitive closure</fr:link> of a finite <fr:link href="jms-00JC.xml" title="Directed graph" addr="jms-00JC" type="local">directed graph</fr:link> by induction on the number of vertices in the graph.</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>In this section, we will study this concept in more detail.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>1836</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KL</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00KL.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Informal examples of inductively defined functions">Informal examples of inductively defined functions</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>An inductive definition on the naturals defines a structure for each number <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> by first defining it for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=0]]></fr:tex> and then specifying how to augment a structure for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=m]]></fr:tex> to a structure for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=m+1]]></fr:tex>. From the point of view of computer programming, inductive definitions proceed by <fr:em>structural recursion</fr:em>. For example, addition of natural numbers can be defined by induction on the second argument (or the first, if you prefer!):</fr:p>
                <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
  \mathsf {add} &\colon  \mathbb {N}^2\to \mathbb {N}
  \\
  \mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (m,0\right )\mathclose {}} &= m
  \\
  \mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (m,n+1\right )\mathclose {}} &= \mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (m,n\right )\mathclose {}}+1
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex>
                <fr:p>Likewise, the function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma \colon  \mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> that takes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> to the sum <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _{0\leq  i < n}i]]></fr:tex> can be defined inductively:</fr:p>
                <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
  \Sigma  &\colon  \mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}\\
  \Sigma {\mathopen {}\left (0\right )\mathclose {}} &= 0\\
  \Sigma {\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}} &= \mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (n,\Sigma {\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>In order to make precise the description of <fr:link href="jms-00JE.xml" title="Iteration of endo-relations" addr="jms-00JE" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00JE" /></fr:link>, <fr:link href="jms-00JV.xml" title="The adjacency matrix of the reflexive-transitive closure" addr="jms-00JV" type="local">Algorithm <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00JV" /></fr:link>, and <fr:link href="jms-00KL.xml" title="Informal examples of inductively defined functions" addr="jms-00KL" type="local">Example <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KL" /></fr:link> as “inductive definitions”, we must give an actual formal definition of what an inductive definition is.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>1837</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KM</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00KM.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Inductively defined function">Inductively defined <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> be a set, and fix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \mathbb {N}\times  A\to  A]]></fr:tex>. The <fr:em><fr:strong><fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> inductively defined from</fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is defined to be the unique <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon \mathbb {N}\to  A]]></fr:tex> satisfying the following equations:</fr:p>
                <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
  \mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (0\right )\mathclose {}} &= a\\
  \mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}} &= f{\mathopen {}\left (n,\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Note that our specification of inductively defined <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">functions</fr:link> in <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KM" /></fr:link> asserts, without proof, that there does in fact exist a unique function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon \mathbb {N}\to  A]]></fr:tex> satisfying the described equations. It is not blindingly obvious that this claim is true — and, after seeing a few examples to motivate <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KM" /></fr:link>, we will explicitly justify <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KM" /></fr:link> by means of an existence theorem.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>1838</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KN</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00KN.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Formal examples of inductively defined functions">Formal examples of <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">inductively defined functions</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We have seen two informal examples of inductive definitions in <fr:link href="jms-00KL.xml" title="Informal examples of inductively defined functions" addr="jms-00KL" type="local">Example <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KL" /></fr:link>; we will now update these examples in light of <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KM" /></fr:link>:</fr:p>
                <fr:ul><fr:li>For every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (m,-\right )\mathclose {}}\colon \mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{m,{\mathopen {}\left (i,n\right )\mathclose {}}\mapsto  n+1}]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">inductively defined</fr:link> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (i,n\right )\mathclose {}} = n+1]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
 <fr:li>The function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma \colon \mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> taking <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _{0\leq  i<n}i]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{0,\mathsf {add}}]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">inductively defined</fr:link> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {add}\colon  \mathbb {N}\times \mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ul>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>1839</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KO</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00KO.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span> <fr:link href="jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Given an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> and a <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \mathbb {N}\times  A \to  A]]></fr:tex>, we call a <fr:link href="jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> whenever we have both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\mathrel {R}a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mathrel {R}x\implies  {\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}\mathrel {R}f{\mathopen {}\left (n,x\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>In light of <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KO" /></fr:link>, we see that <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">Definition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KM" /></fr:link> is defining <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}]]></fr:tex> to be the unique <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link> <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link>. We still have to show that this exists.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>1841</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KP</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00KP.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Existence of inductively defined functions">Existence of <fr:link href="jms-00KM.xml" title="Inductively defined function" addr="jms-00KM" type="local">inductively defined functions</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Given an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> and a <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \mathbb {N}\times  A\to  A]]></fr:tex>, now let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon  \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> be the intersection of all the <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span> relations</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>The <fr:link href="jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon  \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">functional</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">total</fr:link>, and therefore a <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link>.</fr:li>
 <fr:li>The <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon  \mathbb {N}\to  A]]></fr:tex> is the unique <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link> <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link>, i.e. it is the unique <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> satisfying both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (0\right )\mathclose {}}=a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  n\in \mathbb {N}\mathpunct {.} \mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}=f{\mathopen {}\left (n,\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{n}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ol>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>1840</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/692</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-692.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We first notice that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon  \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> is itself <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link>, which can be seen by observing that the intersection of a set of <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span> relations</fr:link> is <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link>. With this in hand, we proceed.</fr:p>

 <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:p>We must show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon  \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link>.</fr:p>

   <fr:ol><fr:li>To show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon  \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">functional</fr:link>, we must show that for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in  A]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}} x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}y]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=y]]></fr:tex>. We proceed to prove <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P{\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}} = \forall  x,y\in  A\mathpunct {.} n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}} x \land  n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}y\implies  x=y]]></fr:tex> by induction on <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>.</html:span>

     <fr:ol><fr:li><fr:p>For the base case, we fix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}} y]]></fr:tex> to check that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=y]]></fr:tex>. By definition, we know that for any <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span> relation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> we both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\mathrel {R}x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\mathrel {R}y]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
       <fr:p>We choose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be the union of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{{\mathopen {}\left (0,a\right )\mathclose {}}\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{{\mathopen {}\left (n,x\right )\mathclose {}}\,\middle \vert \,n > 0 \land  n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}} x\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, which is <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link>; we have used the fact that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link>. As this union is disjoint, we can see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\mathrel {R}z]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=a]]></fr:tex>, so we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=a=y]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:li>
      <fr:li><fr:p>In the inductive step, we assume <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P{\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> to prove <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. Fixing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}y]]></fr:tex>, we must show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=y]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
       <fr:p>We know that for any <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span> relation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> we have both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}\mathrel {R}x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}\mathrel {R}y]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

       <fr:p>We choose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> to be the union of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{{\mathopen {}\left (m+1,f{\mathopen {}\left (m,z\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}\,\middle \vert \,m=n\land  m\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}{z}\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{{\mathopen {}\left (m,z\right )\mathclose {}}\,\middle \vert \,m\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}z\land  m\not =n+1\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, noting that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link> because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link>. As the union defining <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is disjoint, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in  A]]></fr:tex> we know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}\mathrel {R}z]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=f{\mathopen {}\left (n,z'\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z']]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}} z']]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
       <fr:p>Therefore, we have some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x',y'\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=f{\mathopen {}\left (n,x'\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y=f{\mathopen {}\left (n,y'\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}} x']]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}y']]></fr:tex>. By our inductive hypothesis, we know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x'=y']]></fr:tex>, and hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=y]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:li></fr:ol></fr:li>

    <fr:li><fr:p>To show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon  \mathbb {N}\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">total</fr:link>, we must show that for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}{\downarrow }]]></fr:tex>. This is proved by induction on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
     <fr:ol><fr:li>In the base case, we deduce <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (0\right )\mathclose {}}{\downarrow }]]></fr:tex> from our asumption that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}a]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
      <fr:li>In the inductive step, we assume that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}{\downarrow }]]></fr:tex> and must show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}{\downarrow }]]></fr:tex>. By our assumption, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{{\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}}]]></fr:tex>; because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span> relation</fr:link>, we may conclude <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}}\mathrel {\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}}f{\mathopen {}\left (n,\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:li></fr:ol></fr:li>

  <fr:li>It remains to show that the <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon \mathbb {N}\to  A]]></fr:tex> is the unique <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closed</html:span></fr:link> <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link>. This too can be proved by induction, as <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">functionality</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00KO.xml" title="{\mathopen{}\left(a,f\right)\mathclose{}}-closed relation" addr="jms-00KO" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,f\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>-closure</html:span></fr:link> fully specify the <fr:link href="jms-00KA.xml" title="Values of partial functions" addr="jms-00KA" type="local">values</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}]]></fr:tex> on all inputs.</fr:li></fr:ol>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
