            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KM</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00KM.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Inductively defined function">Inductively defined <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> be a set, and fix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \mathbb {N}\times  A\to  A]]></fr:tex>. The <fr:em><fr:strong><fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> inductively defined from</fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is defined to be the unique <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}\colon \mathbb {N}\to  A]]></fr:tex> satisfying the following equations:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
  \mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (0\right )\mathclose {}} &= a\\
  \mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}} &= f{\mathopen {}\left (n,\mathbf {\rho }_{a,f}{\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
              <fr:contributor>
                <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
              </fr:contributor>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>1</fr:month>
              <fr:day>23</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>10394</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KL</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00KL.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Informal examples of inductively defined functions">Informal examples of inductively defined functions</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An inductive definition on the naturals defines a structure for each number <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> by first defining it for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=0]]></fr:tex> and then specifying how to augment a structure for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=m]]></fr:tex> to a structure for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=m+1]]></fr:tex>. From the point of view of computer programming, inductive definitions proceed by <fr:em>structural recursion</fr:em>. For example, addition of natural numbers can be defined by induction on the second argument (or the first, if you prefer!):</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
  \mathsf {add} &\colon  \mathbb {N}^2\to \mathbb {N}
  \\
  \mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (m,0\right )\mathclose {}} &= m
  \\
  \mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (m,n+1\right )\mathclose {}} &= \mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (m,n\right )\mathclose {}}+1
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Likewise, the function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma \colon  \mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> that takes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> to the sum <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _{0\leq  i < n}i]]></fr:tex> can be defined inductively:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
  \Sigma  &\colon  \mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}\\
  \Sigma {\mathopen {}\left (0\right )\mathclose {}} &= 0\\
  \Sigma {\mathopen {}\left (n+1\right )\mathclose {}} &= \mathsf {add}{\mathopen {}\left (n,\Sigma {\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
              <fr:contributor>
                <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
              </fr:contributor>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>1</fr:month>
              <fr:day>22</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>10395</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KF</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00KF.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Function">Function</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:link href="jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">partial function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B]]></fr:tex> is called <fr:em><fr:strong>total</fr:strong></fr:em> whenever its <fr:link href="jms-00KB.xml" title="Domain of definition of a partial function" addr="jms-00KB" type="local">domain of definition</fr:link> coincides with its domain (source), i.e. we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}{\downarrow }]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>. In this case, we will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> and refer to it as a <fr:em><fr:strong>function</fr:strong></fr:em> or a <fr:em><fr:strong>map</fr:strong></fr:em>. Sometimes, we redundantly refer to it as a <fr:em><fr:strong>total function</fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Just as we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Rel}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>for the sets of <fr:link href="jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relations</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">partial functions</fr:link> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> respectively, we shall write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A\to  B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for the set of functions from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
